    <h3>EXERCISES</h3>

    <div class="exercise">
        <span class="exercise-type reflection">Reflection</span>
        <h4>Your Debate History</h4>
        <p>Think about the last time you changed your mind about something important. What happened? Was it an argument someone made, an experience you had, or something else? Now think about the last time someone changed their mind because of something you said. What was different about that conversation compared to arguments that go nowhere?</p>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
        <span class="exercise-type practice">Practice</span>
        <h4>The Steel Man Challenge</h4>
        <p>Choose a political or social position you strongly disagree with. Spend fifteen minutes writing the strongest possible argument for that position. Don't strawman it. Don't mock it. Make it genuinely persuasive. If you can't do this, you don't understand the opposition well enough to argue against it effectively.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
        <span class="exercise-type challenge">Challenge</span>
        <h4>The Dinner Table Debate</h4>
        <p>The next time you're in a conversation where disagreement arises, try introducing structure. Suggest that each person get two minutes to make their case without interruption. Then each person gets one minute to respond. Notice how the structure changes the quality of the exchange. Did people listen differently? Did the conversation feel more productive?</p>
